Evolving Solutions for Iterated Prisoners Dilemma
\layout Author

Marko Grönroos
\layout Abstract

This artice describes the Prisoners application for NeHeP evolutionary algorithm
 library.
 The application evolves a strategy for Iterated Prisoner's Dilemma in a
 group of various other standard strategies: Co-operating, Defecting, Tit-for-Ta
t, and random.
 The prisoners compete one-on-one against every other strategy and have
 a memory of three previous decisions.
 An evolved strategy is usually found to yield better results than the Tit-for-T
at strategy.
\layout Section

Introduction
\layout Standard

Prisoner's Dilemma (PD) is a hypothetical situation where two crime partners
 have been arrested for questioning.
 If one of the two blames the other (defects him), and the other stays silent
 (co-operates), the defecting prisoner gets free and the co-operating gets
 5 years of prison.
 If both stay silent, both get 1 year in prison.
 If both blame the other, both get 3 years.
\layout Standard

Iterative Prisoner's Dilemma (IPD) is an extended variant of the PD, where
 each pair of prisoners are questioned for a number of times.
 Each time the prisoners remember the decisions in three previous times
 and can act according to those decisions.
 For example, if the other prisoner defected previously, it is possible
 to revenge that by defecting now.
\layout Standard

The problem belongs to game theory, and is relevant for many fields of natural
 sciences and philosophy, including sociology, economics, biology, ethology,
 and evolutionary theory.
