Competing strategies
\layout Standard


\emph on 
Tit-for-tat
\emph default 
 strategy means simply co-operating on the first iteration and after that
 doing what the other prisoner did previously.
 If the other prisoner had co-operated previously, we trust him to co-operate
 again, and if he defected previously, we do not trust him to co-operate
 this time but 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

revenge
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 by defecting.
 If the other prisoner always co-operates, both will always get only 1 year.
 If the other prisoner always defects, both always get 3 years.
 If the other prisoner is also a tit-for-tat strategy, both co-operate.
 This strategy is very good when competing against other strategies.
\layout Standard

The real problem is to find an evolutionary strategy that does better, on
 average, than tit-for-tat strategy.
